"Ansuategi A., Escapa M.","Economic growth and greenhouse gas emissions",2002,"Ecological Economics","40","1",,"23","37",,,10.1016/S0921-8009(01)00272-5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0036160569&partnerID=40&md5=3088e6b8db14d2e2ff4e8d51578fefa9","Ekonomi Zientzien Fakultatea, Lehendakari Agirre Etorbidea 83, 48015 Bilbao, Spain","Ansuategi, A., Ekonomi Zientzien Fakultatea, Lehendakari Agirre Etorbidea 83, 48015 Bilbao, Spain; Escapa, M., Ekonomi Zientzien Fakultatea, Lehendakari Agirre Etorbidea 83, 48015 Bilbao, Spain","Recent empirical research has examined the relationship between certain indicators of environmental degradation and income, concluding that in some cases an inverted U-shaped relationship, which has been called an environmental Kuznets curve (EKC), exists between these variables. Unfortunately, this inverted U-shaped relationship does not hold for greenhouse gas emissions. One explanation of the absence of EKC-like behavior in greenhouse gas emissions is that greenhouse gases are special pollutants that create global, not local, disutility. But the international nature of global warming is not the only reason that prevents de-linking greenhouse gas emissions from economic growth. The intergenerational nature of the negative impact of greenhouse gas emissions may have also been an important factor preventing the implementation of greenhouse gas abatement measures in the past. In this paper we explore the effect that the presence of intergenerational spillovers has on the emissions-income relationship. We use a numerically calibrated overlapping generations model of climate-economy interactions. We conclude that: (1) the intertemporal responsibility of the regulatory agency, (2) the institutional capacity to make intergenerational transfers and (3) the presence of intergenerationally lagged impact of emissions constitute important determinants of the relationship between economic growth and greenhouse gas emissions. © 2002 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved.","Climate change; Environmental Kuznets Curve; Intergenerational externalities","economic growth; greenhouse gas; intergenerational transfer; Kuznets curve",,,,,,"Alcamo, J., Bouwman, A., Edmonds, J., Grüber, A., Morita, T., Sugnadhy, A., An evaluation of the IPCC IS92 emission scenarios (1995) Climate Change 1994: Radiative Forcing of Climate Change and an Evaluation of the IPCC IS92 Emission Scenarios (IPCC special report), , Houghton, J.T., Filho, L.G.M., Bruce, J., Lee, H., Callander, A., Haites, E., Harris, N., Maskell, K. (Eds.). Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; Ansuategi, A., (1999) When smoke gets in your eyes; reconsidering the EKC, , Environment Department Discussion Paper 9904, University of York; Ansuategi, A., Perrings, C., (1999) Intergenerational Externalities in the Environmental Transition Hypothesis, , Mimeo; Ansuategi, A., Perrings, C., Transboundary externalities in the environmental transition hypothesis (2000) Environ. Resour. Econ., 17 (4), pp. 353-373; Ansuategi, A., Barbier, E.B., Perrings, C., The environmental Kuznets curve (1998) Economic Modelling of Sustainable Development: Between Theory and Practice, , van den Bergh, J.C.J.M., Hofkes, M.W. (Eds.). Kluwer Academic Press, Dordrecht; Arrow, K., Bolin, B., Costanza, R., Dasgupta, P., Folke, C., Holling, C.S., Jansson, B.-O., Pimentel, D., Economic growth, carrying capacity and the environment (1995) Science, 268, pp. 520-521; Barbier, E.D., Introduction to the environmental Kuznets curve special issue (1997) Environ. Dev. Econ., 2 (4), pp. 369-382; Cass, D., Optimum growth in an aggregative model of capital accumulation (1965) Rev. Econ. Stud., 32, pp. 233-240; Cesar, H., (1994) Control and Game Models of the Greenhouse Effect, , Springer, Berlin; Cole, M.A., Rayner, A.J., Bates, J.M., The environmental Kuznets curve: An empirical analysis (1997) Environ. Dev. Econ., 2 (4), pp. 401-416; Grossman, G.M., Krueger, A.B., (1991) Environmental Impacts 